<article>
    <h1>Wind tur&#xAD;bine at Pu&#xAD;lau Se&#xAD;makau can power about 35 flats</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201127/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-11-27"><time>2020-11-27</time></a>
        - <span>SINGAPORE</span>
        - <span role="byline">Fabian Koh fabkoh@sph.com.sg</span>
    </section>

    <p>A mas­sive wind tur­bine that stands on Sin­ga­pore’s Pu­lau Se­makau, about 8km south of the main­land, can gen­er­ate enough wind en­ergy to power around 35 Hous­ing Board flats an­nu­ally.</p>
    <p>Tow­er­ing at 42.5m, the three­blade wind tur­bine, con­structed by French en­ergy firm Engie, pro­duces about 20 kilo­watts of elec­tric­ity per hour, based on the wind con­di­tions in Sin­ga­pore.</p>
    <p>At that rate, it can gen­er­ate enough en­ergy to power be­tween 30 and 35 HDB flats of var­i­ous sizes in a year, said an Engie spokesman.</p>
    <p>Ac­cord­ing to the Na­tional Cli­mate Change Sec­re­tariat web­site, com­mer­cial wind tur­bines op­er­ate at wind speeds of above 4.5m per sec­ond, but the av­er­age wind speed in Sin­ga­pore is only about 2m per sec­ond.</p>
    <p>The wind tur­bine is part of a re­search and de­vel­op­ment fa­cil­ity at Se­makau Land­fill launched yes­ter­day by the French firm’s lo­cal re­search arm, Engie Lab Sin­ga­pore, to test new clean en­ergy tech­nol­ogy.</p>
    <p>The fa­cil­ity also has a platform to gen­er­ate elec­tri­cal en­ergy from hy­dro­gen fuel, and a re­fu­elling sta­tion for elec­tri­cal ve­hi­cles.</p>
    <p>The launch was wit­nessed by Mr Marc Aben­sour, the French Am­bas­sador to Sin­ga­pore.</p>
    <p>The project was de­vel­oped in col­lab­o­ra­tion with the Re­new­able En­ergy In­te­gra­tion Demon­stra­tor Sin­ga­pore pro­gramme, un­der Nanyang Tech­no­log­i­cal Univer­sity’s (NTU) En­ergy Re­search In­sti­tute, which looks at sus­tain­able and af­ford­able en­ergy ac­cess in South-east Asia and fu­ture elec­tric­ity dis­tri­bu­tion in ur­ban ar­eas.</p>
    <p>Engie Lab Sin­ga­pore man­ag­ing di­rec­tor Loic Vil­lo­cel called the fa­cil­ity a timely ad­di­tion, given the in­creas­ing fo­cus in Sin­ga­pore on low-car­bon en­ergy re­search and the use of hy­dro­gen.</p>
    <p>Pro­fes­sor Lam Khin Yong, se­nior vice-pres­i­dent of re­search at NTU, said the project is one of the largest liv­ing test beds man­aged by the univer­sity’s re­searchers, in­te­grat­ing mul­ti­ple en­ergy sources and stor­age so­lu­tions to re­duce the Repub­lic’s car­bon foot­print.</p>

